POPS:
THE NEXT GENERATION
TO STRENGTHEN INDICATORS FOR POPS WILL REQUIRE IMPROVEMENTS IN POP AIR MONITORING AND MODELING IN
ORDER TO ESTABLISH MODELED EMISSIONS RATES FOR POPS AT THE COUNTRY, REGION, OR GLOBAL LEVEL.

INCREASE SPATIAL COVERAGE OF AIR MEASUREMENTS WITH PASSIVE AIR
SAMPLERS. SUCH MEASUREMENTS SHOULD BE SUSTAINED AND EXPANDED.
PASSIVE SAMPLERS CAPABLE OF SAMPLING PARTICLE-PHASE COMPOUNDS
SHOULD ALSO BE EXPLORED.
DEVELOPING EXPERTISE IN ALL ASPECTS OF AIR MONITORING WILL ENSURE
THE DELIVERY OF COMPARABLE DATA. THIS INCLUDES AIR SAMPLING, CHEMICAL
ANALYSIS, DATA MANAGEMENT, INTERNATIONAL AND REGIONAL
INTERLABORATORY COMPARISONS, DATA QA/QC AND INTERPRETATION.
SUCH DATA CAN HELP BUILD MODELS, UNDERSTAND TRANSPORT, ASSESS
CHANGES IN EMISSIONS OVER TIME, AND EVALUATE CONTROL MEASURES.
ENHANCE RESEARCH ON THE STABILITY OF PARTICLE-BOUND CHEMICALS. THIS
IS VERY RELEVANT IN URBAN AREAS OF DEVELOPING REGIONS WHERE
INCREASES IN AIR-BORNE PARTICLES LEAD TO INCREASED HUMAN EXPOSURE.
ALSO, IT WOULD HELP TO CO-LOCATE POP MONITORING AT EXISTING
MONITORING STATIONS FOR AIR QUALITY AND METEOROLOGY, TO CUT COSTS
AND BOOST UNDERSTANDING OF RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN CO-POLLUTANTS.
FACILITATE DATA SHARING WITH ATMOSPHERIC POLLUTANT DATA ARCHIVES
THAT INCLUDE AIR MONITORING DATA OF POPS (E.G. AMAP/EMEP DATABASE),
PROVIDING A FOUNDATION FOR MODEL AND INDICATOR DEVELOPMENT.
SUPPLEMENT EXISTING MONITORING PROGRAMS WITH TARGETED
MEASUREMENT CAMPAIGNS IN DESIGNATED SOURCE AREAS THAT, TOGETHER
WITH APPROPRIATE REGIONAL-SCALE MODELING, WILL PROVIDE EMISSION
ESTIMATES THAT CAN BE EXTRAPOLATED TO SIMILAR REGIONS. EMISSION
ESTIMATES FROM THESE CAMPAIGNS SHOULD BE USED TO DRIVE GLOBAL
MODELS.
